                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">(if you want to get to the point without all the rest scroll to the bottom and start from "So my suggestion is this:")
<br />

<br />
Charm is not broken.
<br />

<br />
Lets face facts folks, Charm isn't broken - the mobs are.
<br />

<br />
If charm was broken then an Orc Pawn in East Commonlands when charmed with Command of Druzzil (CoD) would hit like any other pet that was charmed with CoD. It does not matter how many buffs you give that orc pawn, it will never hit for 1300 nor have 20,000 HP.
<br />

<br />
In fact all Charm does is allow you to command a mob as if it was a normal pet. The ability to command a pet isn't broken either, so it must be the mob.
<br />

<br />
Charm has an innate risk, unlike a normal pet a charmed pet will at some random point turn on its "master". Due to this fact a lot of people have never been keen on using this line of spells. The random, warningless, nature of the spell put even more people off.
<br />

<br />
The Developers have stated that mobs significantly increase their power each expansion "to keep the game challenging". This is a trend that always has been and will continue for the future.
<br />

<br />
Lets look at some of the "trash" mobs folk have been fighting over the years. Not bosses but the kind of mobs you would expect to be in an exp group and fighting, on average.
<br />

<br />
EQ, ~80
<br />
RoS, ~150
<br />
SoV, ~200
<br />
SoL, ~250
<br />
PoP, ~600
<br />
LoY, ~&lt;200 (mid level expansion though)
<br />
LDoN, ~500-1000 (depending on difficutly settings)
<br />
GoD, ~1300
<br />
OoW, ~800 (but hitting much faster than before)
<br />

<br />
As you can see the amount mobs hit for has increased significantly during each expansion. After SoL it was &gt;double the increase and then &gt;double again for the next raid expasion (GoD). Although there was a significant increase in damage compared to the SoL and PoP mobs their HP remained about the same, in most cases it was actually slightly less in PoP. This was balanced by other factors.
<br />
However, such an incremental increase in damage without an equivelant increase in HP allowed charming to come to an obvious advantage. Previously any increase in damage had been offset by an equal or greater increase in HP, meaning that mobs took just as long to kill.
<br />
PoP introduced the ability to charm a mob that could kill its equivelent with relative ease. Enchanters were not the only class with this ability, Necromancers, Mages and Druids could also do this. Enchanters however did have the widest range of choices to charm from and so it was Enchanters that became the most visable.
<br />

<br />
With the changes in mob damage introduced in Planes of Power (PoP) the "risk vs reward" (RvR) of charm became very obvious. The more folk that were doing it the more folk saw just how good it was. Now what had been a decent ability that was rarely used and even less commonly seen, by others, became commonplace. In fact it became so common that in some situations it was a viable tactic to complete a goal.
<br />
As the publicity of this spell grew so did the complaints. These complaints lead to a large number of changes.(As to wether any of these changes were good or bad should be left to another thread (please)). Suffice to say that none of the changes actually had any effect on Charm, only in the manner and desirability of its use.
<br />
Charm wasn't really a group tactic, a lot of people used it by themselves (solo) or with friends.
<br />
The majority only every really saw it or read about it. The only charm they really wanted was Dire Charm (DC) as this didn't, normally, break and gave some decent damage to the group - but with no additional risk.
<br />

<br />
I'm going to skip Legacy of Ykesha (LoY) as i was to high a level to really experiance any of its content.
<br />

<br />
So onto Lost Dungeons of Norrath (LDoN). Charming by now was commonplace among Enchanters and largely ignored by the other capable classes due to a lack of charmable content, for them. Still Charm was veiwed by a lot of folk as "to risky" to be used in a group. Even as a viable group tactic for those experianced enough to use it, charm was risky if the rest of the group didn't know what to expect. An un-experianced group was more likely to die to a pet than most other situations in the game.
<br />
Due to the massive useage in PoP for solo content a lot more Enchaters were happy with using Charm. As people became less wary and more appreciative of charm its popularity grew.
<br />

<br />
Now we get to GoD. Charm has become pretty much accepted as a decent source of damage for a group. Folk are still wary about it but its recognised.
<br />
The mobs in GoD hit hard, very hard. For the majority of the players it represents a 300-500% increase in damage, for these players it is impossible to effectivly group.
<br />
Eventually there were several "changes" made to the entire expansion that decrease the average output to a more 200-300% increase. This modified increase is still more than a lot of people can handle, but much like PoP you got used to it after a while.
<br />
To advance in this expansion required the work of single groups. Previous expansions used entire raids to advance, since the onus was now on the group makeup rather than the numbers different tactics were required. Due to the increase in damage the players had to take virtually none of the "traditional" tricks could be used, except by those right at the very top of the game that had the gear and the experiance to handle this type of mob. (the top teir mobs in PoP did the same kind of damage)
<br />
(The most significant zones in GoD were Tipt and Vxed. These 2 zones were the main point of contestation for advancement and the main point where the damage increase was felt.)
<br />
Due to the initial increase in dificutly a new tactic was formed, around Charm. Because mobs were now so powerful that most folk could not effectivly group they found something that could take the beating, instead of them. As it happened other mobs could take this beating. Due to this people started to rely on charmed pets to either make the fight much shorter so that the other mob didn't have time to kill the players or fight by itself.
<br />
(A little remembered fact is that before the change druids could effectivly charm in both Tipt and Vxed. After the change the mob level was increased to a range where Druids were unable to do this.)
<br />
Now that charm is recognised as the single easiest method of "beating" these 2 areas of the game it becomes common in groups. For the majority of the players it becomes the *only* method. Charm is also now extreamly risky, the one class that can do this has an average of about 5000-6000hp. Their "pets" hit for about 1300 on average per round. This gives the Enchanter about 3 rounds to live, or almost enough time to recive a heal if the healer is being attentive. Due to this risk to the Enchanter and the fact that without the Enchanter the group cannot succeed, tactics were refined to make charming as risk free as possible.
<br />
Now the entire group is focused around one thing, Charm.
<br />
(Of course it is perfectly possible to "beat" these zones without the use of charm, it is just harder. As with most things in nature, Humans will generally take the easiest route.)
<br />
Now that charm is percived to be the only way of doing content that has this much damage, the fact that it can be made to be "almost" risk free and that is recieving so much publicity. Something has to be done to break the mold.
<br />

<br />
So we have gone from something that was pretty obscure and mainly ignored, in some cases not even heard of, to something that is the entire focus of a large % of the game players. With this much demand created and centered around just 1 spell, CoD, the common perception that the spell was at fault came into being. So I'll ask you again to think about that Orc Pawn.
<br />

<br />
With the release of Omens of War (OoW) the usual spells were received. This included new Charms. Charm was not changed in any way. You can still use the highest level of OoW charm and the Orc Pawn will stil have the same results.
<br />
The mobs were changed. They seem to have been changed in the simplest of ways, by limiting the amout of damage they can do whilst charmed. This, however, only became effective in the OoW zones, no previous expansions were changed. To top it off any mobs in perviuos expansion that were normally un-charmable due to level are also un-charmable with the new spells, however the mobs that were charmable before are still charmable with the new spells.
<br />

<br />
The way the "new charm" system works can be broken down to a simple form;
<br />
A mob will, whilst charmed, hit for a maximum of only 250 damage. (of course the figures vary slightly but not much) The problem is that before the mob was charmed it hit for 800 and after it breaks charm it will hit for 800. The major problem being is that whilst there is great risk involved with charming a mob for 800, there is little reward for charming that mob if it will only hit for 250. There is even less reward when the mob breaks its charm and imeadiatly hits the Enchanter or another group member for 800.
<br />
Charm goes back into its "to risky for the group" category that was around before PoP.
<br />

<br />
Ironically the areas that the problem was first identified by the majority of players has in no way been affected by this change. Charm is still considered the "only" way to beat those 2 zones, by the majority.
<br />

<br />
So, you might say that the mob should only hit for 250 after it breaks. It can't be done, i'll explain why.
<br />
In another expansion or 2 mobs will hit for exponantially more (again). So now we have mobs that, lets say, hit for 3000. Charmed they hit for 400. Now conventially you would slow a mob and then proceed to kill it. With a mob that only hits for 400 after it breaks charm, even for only 30 seconds, the content is totally trivialised - the other term for this is exploit. The only way around this is to increase the damage the mob does whilst charmed, which nullifies the point, or to make it too risky to actually charm in the first place.
<br />
So we will never see mobs that sustain mitigated damage after a charm break.
<br />
Without the ability for an enchanter to survive a charm break there is literally no incentive to actually charm, ergo charm is no longer useful. Except its still "required" in another part of the game.
<br />
This is one of the major gripes of the Enchanters, a spell that has been so useful for so long has been made extinct, yet it is still belived to be a "core" ability even when no one will use it - in this expansion.
<br />

<br />
The whole point of all these changes is to "balance", not charm, but one class against another. When taken into consideration "balancing charm" can never be done, the Orc Pawn will have just as many problems as it always has.
<br />
Looked at another way you could say *Charm will never be balanced*.
<br />

<br />
If you say that charm can never be balanced then you can also say that its better off dead. Appart from 1 slight problem where several encounters seem to have been written specifically to use charm - or be virtually unwinnable by the majority. This counts for raid encounters as well as exp groups. Eradicating charm in its totallity would also upset a lot of players and "viablity". It is only the new expansion and Tipt/Vxed where the major problems are currently found.
<br />

<br />
So if the pre-OoW charms have effectivly been written into the game and can't be changed without breaking content, in fact they have not been changed at all, then the line could end there and almost no one would really mind. Appart from the fact that the existing problems would still exist but no change to charm has ever changed the pre-existing problems.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So my suggestion is this:
<br />

<br />
Make all current OoW charms do something else.
<br />

<br />
Repeatedly SoE representatives at varying levels have said that Enchanters are not a pet class. Repeatedly we have been given new charm spells to make pets with. Any class that can make a pet is by definition a "pet class". However if pets are not to be our primary ability, which seems to be the current trend and charm is getting to complex to "balance". It is time for a change.
<br />

<br />
Make the OoW charms create an "illusion". Illusions are supposed to be one of our primary abilities but we never really do anything with it.
<br />
These new Illusions are quite simply the delusions of the targeted creature. Beliefe becomes reality and so the illusions cause damage. Beacause the illusions are "delusions" of another creature we have no control over them and so are not pets.
<br />
You could have these delusions do any number of interesting things, from the plain old damage to reducing stats/abilites or even reducing stats/hp (both/either) and increasing something else "%T becomes delusional and goes into a state of fury"
<br />
If the Illusions were effected by the AA "Total Domination" it would continue the usefulness of that AA - you are after all "dominating" the reality of the affected mob.
<br />

<br />
The benefit of these "illusions" is that they are completely tailorable to any balancing requirements. Instead of directly using the content to effect the content, Enchanters would be like every other class in using their abilities to effect that content. Or, Enchanters will only increase at the same rate as other classes (as designated by the SoE team) instead of increasing at the same rate as the content.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
