                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The first thing to remember is, EQ is about DPS.  Everything else exists to support DPS.
<br />

<br />
A tank who is immune to all damage forever will earn XP at a rate determined by group DPS.  All the tank does is provide the mechanism for the DPS to act.  The same is true of pulling, healing, slowing and everything else.
<br />

<br />
In PoP and beyond, player defences have been increasing faster than player DPS.  DPS goes up, but not by the same amount.
<br />

<br />
Defence is different than DPS, in that once your have enough defence, every additional unit of Defence doesn't help at all.  Meanwhile having twice the DPS means you can kill creatures twice as fast.
<br />

<br />
Creatures that used to require 5+ healers to heal (say, 1100 hitting L 66 beasts) are now one groupable due to defence (heal, debuff, tank) increases.
<br />

<br />
The DPS of mobs is purportional to player defence.  Because defence has been growing faster than player DPS, this means mob DPS has been growing faster than mob DPS.
<br />

<br />
Player DPS has been growing slower.  Remember Luclin?  Mobs that where difficult due to HPs are not difficult, they just take forever to kill and are boring.  You made them easier by upping your DPS.  PoP and beyond creatures are difficult because of their DPS, and you make them easier by upping your defence (mainly) and DPS (secondarially).
<br />

<br />
If Player DPS grew as fast as player Defence, old zones would become trivial faster.  You can't single group VT because while the defence of a single group of Qvic geared players may match a raid of Ssra-geared players, the DPS of a single group of Qvic players is nothing next to the raid of Ssra-geared players.  With enough DPS, old content dies instantly and quickly, as opposed to faster but not instantly.
<br />

<br />
DPS is also the means by which XP is metered.  A doubling of DPS doubles XP.  A doubling of defence doesn't have to.
<br />

<br />
So player DPS is kept under control.  Which means mob hps grow slower than mob DPS and player Defence.
<br />

<br />
Which leads to the charm problem.  Mob DPS is diverging, being balanced against player defence.  Mob defence isn't growing as fast as player defence is.  So a mob attacking a mob has insane DPS against a low defence target.  The result: charm becomes overly powerful.
<br />

<br />
I understand their problem.
<br />

<br />
I just disagree with the solution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Charm goes back into its "to risky for the group" category that was around before PoP.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It wasn't too risky, because pre-xp changes the best xp came from low blues.  Low blues are easy to keep under control charmed and are low risk for decent reward.  Once you where fighting high cons this changed.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">So, you might say that the mob should only hit for 250 after it breaks. It can't be done, i'll explain why.
<br />
In another expansion or 2 mobs will hit for exponantially more (again). So now we have mobs that, lets say, hit for 3000. Charmed they hit for 400. Now conventially you would slow a mob and then proceed to kill it. With a mob that only hits for 400 after it breaks charm, even for only 30 seconds, the content is totally trivialised - the other term for this is exploit. The only way around this is to increase the damage the mob does whilst charmed, which nullifies the point, or to make it too risky to actually charm in the first place. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The confused loyalties effect has a 1000 hp 100% spell/melee mitigation effect (this works on dots and on melee damage).  When the effect goes away, so does confused loyalties.  The result is you can't damage the mob while the mob is in gimped mode without freeing the mob from gimped mode.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">So we will never see mobs that sustain mitigated damage after a charm break.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unless the problem you describe can be solved.  =)
<br />

<br />
If a gimped pet cannot be killed, the gimpyness of the DPS isn't a problem.  You can make sure that damaging a gimped pet frees the pet from gimpyness.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
