                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Show me where any other classes' new spells and abilities don't impact existing content</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Show me another class spell that has recieved as much publicity as charm, without being nerfed.
<br />

<br />
I'll give you one example - ManaBurn vs IHT.
<br />

<br />
Some Wizards went on a MB spree on their servers and as a result the ability has been effectivly destroyed - The reason was bad press. Improved Harm Touch does a simular amount of damage and could be used for the same effect, no bad press and no change.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">You started off so well - the mobs are broken. But instead of trying to fix the mobs, you suggested killing charm and making it something entirely different. 
<br />

<br />
My proposal for a fix has been the following: 
<br />
1. Do not scale mob power in relation to player power. If it takes a level 50 mob 20 seconds to kill a player at level 50, then it should take a level 70 mob 20 seconds to kill a player at level 70. 
<br />
2. Old zones were a lot of fun because adds were a common problem. You would need mez, off-tanking, pet-tanking, pacify to try and control the situation. Because of the scaling of mob power, pacify pulling has become the ONLY method for dealing with "challenging" content. Scale back mob power and increase multi-mob encounters and you will have the same challenging content that people enjoyed years ago without having to deal with uber mob that kills enchanters in 6 seconds flat. 
<br />
3. Add new strategies to mob AI so that players have to use varying tactics to beat them. Even with the uber mobs of today, the game can get pretty boring when you just apply the same tactic ad nauseum. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
We are on expansion 8. When in the last 5 expansions has SoE done any of the above suggestions to the majority of an expansion.
<br />
They have been following a trend for years now - with nothing to suggest they are planning to change. In fact they have even said that mob DPS is going to increase to "keep the game challenging".
<br />
The ideas might be what the community wants (lord knows i miss KC and Seb) but the way the game has been created so far would make it hard to "retro" back without trivialising new content.
<br />
Killing off future charms might not be the way to go, but if they continue on the current trend it won't matter. Almost no one will ever use them.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The confused loyalties effect has a 1000 hp 100% spell/melee mitigation effect (this works on dots and on melee damage). When the effect goes away, so does confused loyalties. The result is you can't damage the mob while the mob is in gimped mode without freeing the mob from gimped mode. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Logical method for sustaining reduced DPS for a set time or damage interval.
<br />
It just raises the question - since ideas like this have been banded around recently - why SoE failed to implement something like this, let alone mention it. Recourse effects have been around for a while, adding this effect wouldn't have been hard.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It wasn't too risky, because pre-xp changes the best xp came from low blues. Low blues are easy to keep under control charmed and are low risk for decent reward. Once you where fighting high cons this changed.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
And exactly how common was charm before PoP, outside of Kael and DC mobs in general?
<br />
Sure some of us did it but for the majority of folk it kinda fell into the "whats charm do?" catagory.
<br />
We could go back to killing low blues, but i doubt many folk would stay in our groups since the exp from higher con mobs is far better. So we either charm high con/risk mobs or solo. With the lack of "bait" in newer zones it makes this even harder.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Charm is in no way broken, it is just questionable to being of any usefullness.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
If something was useful to you, yet isn't anymore there is normally a reason. If so many folk are saying Charm is no longer useful, then what happened?
<br />

<br />
What we are looking at is a situation like ManaBurn - we have the bad press. SoE is reacting to it. If you could change it, how?
<br />

<br />
--------
<br />

<br />
So current ideas:
<br />

<br />
Charm break causes a recourse effect that keeps a mob "gimped" for a set duration and/or damage.
<br />
Scale mobs and events to pre-existing content, yet keep it challenging by improving the AI routines.
<br />
The mob is stunned for 2 ticks after breaking charm.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
