                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hmmm ......
<br />

<br />
During the GoD Beta, I played an enchantress as was my usual character at the time.  
<br />

<br />
You mentioned 3 items, 
<br />

<br />
" 1. Do not scale mob power in relation to player power. If it takes a level 50 mob 20 seconds to kill a player at level 50, then it should take a level 70 mob 20 seconds to kill a player at level 70.
<br />
2. Old zones were a lot of fun because adds were a common problem. You would need mez, off-tanking, pet-tanking, pacify to try and control the situation. Because of the scaling of mob power, pacify pulling has become the ONLY method for dealing with "challenging" content. Scale back mob power and increase multi-mob encounters and you will have the same challenging content that people enjoyed years ago without having to deal with uber mob that kills enchanters in 6 seconds flat.
<br />
3. Add new strategies to mob AI so that players have to use varying tactics to beat them. Even with the uber mobs of today, the game can get pretty boring when you just apply the same tactic ad nauseum./"
<br />

<br />
The GoD beta as presented to us, pretty much had these 3 items.  Yes it was possible for a 65 to solo a light blue and some dark blues with minimal buffs, virtue only in many cases some even possible without heals using some stratagies.  The mobs were pretty much scaled.  
<br />

<br />
There were a great many adds necessitaing the enchanter in many cases or at least CC.  I enjoyed the zone in circle where one zoned in to the center of a large circle.  Was a nice challange to see if one could take out the 12 or so mobs in the circle around you vice training them to the next zone, but it was doable.  There were many such encounters.  Again we were playing 65 characters during GoD Beta.  
<br />

<br />
Almost all the mobs had specific weaknesses, and many had strengths which would exclude types of weapons, or needed blows to a specific location or type of attack.  It was a pleasent challange.
<br />

<br />
Overall, I thought GoD would be a nice expansion as I participated in the beta.      
<br />

<br />
All of a sudden, comes release.  Mobs are hitting 4, 6, 8 or more times harder than in Beta.  Mob HP proportioned to make even a trash mob stronger than most boss mobs previous to that.  Attack back to the zerg type of attack previlant in many top end raining guilds.  And no Level 70 cap or epic upgrades.  Spells and tomes commented on were not there either.  A lot of the content was missing.  It became apparent, the expansion was geared at the last moment solely to be a challange to top rated Time geared guilds and to be so far above anyone else as to be a big joke.  An expansion for the top 1% of the EQ players with all players at the expense of the 99 % of the players who purchased the expansion.   
<br />

<br />
Oh, and wait, it was the beta testers at fault for such a poor expansion.  BS!
<br />

<br />
More than half the content tested was not in the GoD release.
<br />

<br />
When the announcement came out that Ooops, we, SoE, forgot level 70 and a few other things and here is a planned new expansion, OoW, it was apparent to me what was done.  OoW was to try to give back to the players what was previously tested.  Double the money with 2 expansions for the same content.  And once again mobs needed to be scaled up for the top 1%, not the vast 99% of the players.  I didn't waste my time with the OoW beta, I knew what was going to be there already. 
<br />

<br />
And someone was surprised charming became such a useful method to kill GoD mobs.  Not surprising to me.  If a mob is hitting hard enough or has a huge nasty proc or AE, what is the first stratagy to deal with it?  Keep a distance!  I.E. use pets, charmed pets, minimize getting close and maximize DoTs and spells.  Nothing new there.  Or surprising charm became so usefull.  
<br />

<br />
Now enter the next expansion, tested with higher proportioned mobs and higher levels, and release of newer epics.  And a need to "nerf" spell lines and such.  More BS on their part to make it a challange to only some top players.   
<br />

<br />
The fix needs to include both GoD and OoW expansions, making it playable for all EQ players, not cater to only the top guilds on the servers at the expense of the majority of players.   Your 3 items would go a good distance in repairing some of the trash we have been given.  And give the game back some appeal to continue it into the future.  But I doubt it will happen, seems to me it would be at the expense of their newest favorite child, EQ2.  Guess who eventually wins.   
<br />

<br />
My two cents worth.
<br />

<br />
Sigh!
<br />

<br />
Lucilla</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
